<ArticleLayout
  title="Under-Sink Kitchen Storage: What to Check Before You Buy"
  description="Before buying under-sink kitchen storage, check pipes, leaks, moisture, shelf clearance, cleaning product sizes, bin space and whether removable organisers will fit safely."
  category="Kitchen"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with tidy under-sink storage and practical cleaning supplies"
>
  <p>
    The space under the kitchen sink often looks useful, but it can be one of the trickiest
    areas in the kitchen to organise.
  </p>
  <p>
    It may contain pipes, hoses, water filters, cleaning products, bins, dishwasher
    connections, awkward cabinet doors and signs of moisture. The available space can also be
    much smaller than it looks once plumbing and door clearance are considered.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying under-sink shelves, pull-out drawers, baskets, caddies or bins, it is worth
    checking the actual usable space and whether the area is suitable for the items you want
    to store.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader kitchen storage planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/best-kitchen-storage-ideas-small-australian-homes/">Kitchen Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what is already under the sink</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying anything, empty the under-sink area and check what is already there.
  </p>
  <p>You may find:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Cleaning sprays.</li>
    <li>Dishwashing liquid.</li>
    <li>Dishwasher tablets.</li>
    <li>Sponges and cloths.</li>
    <li>Bin bags.</li>
    <li>Pest control products.</li>
    <li>Old bottles.</li>
    <li>Duplicate cleaning products.</li>
    <li>Unused refills.</li>
    <li>Leaking containers.</li>
    <li>Water filters.</li>
    <li>Pipes and hoses.</li>
    <li>Small bins.</li>
    <li>Items that should not be stored near moisture.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This first step is important because under-sink storage problems are often caused by
    clutter rather than lack of storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If expired, empty or duplicate products are removed, the space may become easier to use
    without adding a new organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Check for leaks or moisture first</h2>
  <p>
    Do not install or buy under-sink storage until you have checked for leaks and dampness.
  </p>
  <p>Look for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Water stains.</li>
    <li>Swollen cabinet panels.</li>
    <li>Mould or musty smells.</li>
    <li>Damp cloths or packaging.</li>
    <li>Rusted items.</li>
    <li>Soft cabinet flooring.</li>
    <li>Slow drips from pipes.</li>
    <li>Moisture around hoses or filters.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If there are signs of leaking, fix the leak before adding storage. Organisers can hide
    early warning signs and make water damage harder to notice.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing cardboard, paper towels, food, timber items or anything moisture-sensitive
    directly under the sink if the area is damp or poorly ventilated.
  </p>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage should make the space easier to use, not hide a maintenance problem.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure around the pipes</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink space is rarely a simple rectangle.
  </p>
  <p>
    The pipes, trap, hoses and fittings can interrupt the middle of the cabinet, which means a
    standard shelf or drawer may not fit.
  </p>
  <p>Measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Internal cabinet width.</li>
    <li>Internal cabinet depth.</li>
    <li>Internal cabinet height.</li>
    <li>Pipe position from the side wall.</li>
    <li>Pipe position from the back wall.</li>
    <li>Height of the lowest pipe.</li>
    <li>Space in front of the pipes.</li>
    <li>Space beside the pipes.</li>
    <li>Whether hoses move or need clearance.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not rely only on the cabinet's outside dimensions.
  </p>
  <p>
    An organiser may fit the cabinet width but still clash with the pipework. Adjustable
    shelves or split-level organisers may be more useful than fixed shelves in this area.
  </p>

  <h2>Check door and hinge clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Cabinet doors can reduce the usable space under the sink.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying baskets, pull-out trays or bins, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Door opening width.</li>
    <li>Hinge position.</li>
    <li>Whether the organiser can slide out fully.</li>
    <li>Whether the cabinet has a centre post.</li>
    <li>Whether handles or door frames block access.</li>
    <li>Whether the organiser catches when removed.</li>
    <li>Whether both doors need to be opened for access.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A basket that fits inside the cabinet may still be awkward if it cannot be removed easily
    through the opening.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is especially important in older kitchens, narrow cabinets and rental kitchens where
    the internal cabinet space may be wider than the actual access point.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what should live under the sink</h2>
  <p>
    Not everything belongs under the sink.
  </p>
  <p>
    The area is usually best for items related to washing, cleaning and bin maintenance.
  </p>
  <p>Common under-sink items include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Dishwashing liquid.</li>
    <li>Dishwasher tablets.</li>
    <li>Cleaning sprays.</li>
    <li>Sponges.</li>
    <li>Cloths.</li>
    <li>Bin liners.</li>
    <li>Small rubbish bags.</li>
    <li>Gloves.</li>
    <li>Brushes.</li>
    <li>Sink plugs.</li>
    <li>Cleaning caddies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Food.</li>
    <li>Pet food.</li>
    <li>Paper products.</li>
    <li>Electrical items.</li>
    <li>Timber boards.</li>
    <li>Rarely used chemicals.</li>
    <li>Items that children can access.</li>
    <li>Products damaged by moisture.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If children or pets are in the home, cleaning products should be stored safely and
    according to label directions. An organiser does not replace safe storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Match the organiser to the problem</h2>
  <p>
    Different under-sink organisers solve different problems.
  </p>

  <h3>Stackable shelves</h3>
  <p>
    Stackable shelves can help use vertical space if the cabinet is tall enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    They work best when there is clear space beside or around the pipework.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check shelf height, pipe clearance and whether bottles can stand upright on
    each level.
  </p>

  <h3>Pull-out drawers</h3>
  <p>
    Pull-out drawers can make items easier to reach at the back of the cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>
    They are useful when products are constantly lost behind other items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check whether the drawer can slide out without hitting pipes, hinges,
    cabinet doors or a centre post.
  </p>
  <p>
    In rentals, avoid pull-out systems that require permanent fixing unless approval is clear.
  </p>

  <h3>Open baskets</h3>
  <p>
    Open baskets are simple and removable.
  </p>
  <p>
    They can work well for grouping sprays, cloths, dishwasher tablets or bin liners.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose baskets that are easy to wipe clean and not too tall to remove from the cabinet.
  </p>

  <h3>Cleaning caddies</h3>
  <p>
    A cleaning caddy can be useful if products are carried around the house.
  </p>
  <p>
    It works best for items used together, such as sprays, cloths and gloves.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check that the caddy fits upright under the sink and can be lifted out without hitting the
    pipes.
  </p>

  <h3>Door-mounted storage</h3>
  <p>
    Door-mounted racks can add space for cloths, gloves, brushes or lightweight items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check whether the rack needs screws or adhesive, whether it will stop the
    door closing, and whether it will hit items inside the cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>
    For renters, freestanding or over-door options are usually lower risk than fixed racks.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more rental-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-kitchen-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Renter-Friendly Kitchen Storage: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about bins and waste storage</h2>
  <p>
    Many households use the under-sink area for rubbish, recycling or food scrap bins.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying a bin or bin organiser, measure carefully.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Bin height.</li>
    <li>Bin width.</li>
    <li>Bin depth.</li>
    <li>Lid clearance.</li>
    <li>Whether the bin can be removed easily.</li>
    <li>Whether bags can be changed without dragging the bin.</li>
    <li>Whether pipes block the bin position.</li>
    <li>Whether the bin door or lid hits the cabinet.</li>
    <li>Whether there is enough space for cleaning products as well.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A bin that fits under the sink may still be annoying if the lid cannot open properly or
    the bag cannot be changed easily.
  </p>
  <p>
    If space is tight, it may be better to choose a smaller bin and empty it more often rather
    than forcing an oversized bin into the cabinet.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose materials that handle spills</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage needs to cope with moisture, cleaning products and spills.
  </p>
  <p>Look for organisers that are:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Easy to wipe clean.</li>
    <li>Resistant to moisture.</li>
    <li>Not made from absorbent fabric.</li>
    <li>Stable when loaded.</li>
    <li>Smooth enough not to trap grime.</li>
    <li>Easy to remove for cleaning.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing leaking bottles directly on cabinet surfaces. A tray or basket can help
    contain small spills and make cleaning easier.
  </p>
  <p>
    If using timber, bamboo or fabric storage, consider whether it will handle dampness and
    cleaning product residue.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep daily items easy to reach</h2>
  <p>
    The most frequently used items should be the easiest to reach.
  </p>
  <p>For many households, this means keeping these near the front:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Dishwashing liquid.</li>
    <li>Dishwasher tablets.</li>
    <li>Sponges.</li>
    <li>Cloths.</li>
    <li>Bin bags.</li>
    <li>Daily cleaning spray.</li>
    <li>Gloves.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Less-used items can sit further back or in a separate caddy.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid creating a system where everyday products are hidden behind spare bottles or rarely
    used cleaners.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is quick access, not maximum storage density.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid overfilling the space</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage can become unsafe or impractical when too much is stored there.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid packing the cabinet so tightly that:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Leaks are hard to see.</li>
    <li>Pipes are difficult to access.</li>
    <li>Products fall out.</li>
    <li>Bottles leak unnoticed.</li>
    <li>Bins cannot be removed.</li>
    <li>Cabinet doors struggle to close.</li>
    <li>Cleaning takes too long.</li>
    <li>Children or pets can reach unsafe products.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Leave enough space to inspect the area.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small amount of clear space under the sink can be more useful than another organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Common under-sink storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage can go wrong when the organiser is chosen before the space is checked.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying shelves before measuring pipe clearance.</li>
    <li>Ignoring leaks or dampness.</li>
    <li>Using organisers that block access to plumbing.</li>
    <li>Storing moisture-sensitive items under the sink.</li>
    <li>Choosing baskets that cannot be removed through the door opening.</li>
    <li>Buying pull-out drawers that hit hinges or pipes.</li>
    <li>Overloading door-mounted racks.</li>
    <li>Storing unsafe products within easy reach of children or pets.</li>
    <li>Using absorbent baskets that are hard to clean.</li>
    <li>Filling the area so tightly that leaks are hidden.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The aim is not to use every centimetre. The aim is to make the space safer, cleaner and
    easier to access.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy under-sink storage yet</h2>
  <p>
    You may not need new under-sink storage yet if the real problem is clutter or maintenance.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check whether the space contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Empty bottles.</li>
    <li>Duplicate cleaners.</li>
    <li>Old sponges.</li>
    <li>Leaking products.</li>
    <li>Expired pest control products.</li>
    <li>Items that belong in the laundry or garage.</li>
    <li>Products that are unsafe to store low.</li>
    <li>Signs of water damage.</li>
    <li>A bin that is too large for the cabinet.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If removing these items solves the issue, a new organiser may not be needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    If there is a leak or dampness, solve that first.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple under-sink storage checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying under-sink kitchen storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is the area dry and free from leaks?</li>
    <li>Have I measured around the pipes?</li>
    <li>Have I checked cabinet width, depth and height?</li>
    <li>Will the organiser fit through the door opening?</li>
    <li>Will it block access to plumbing?</li>
    <li>Can bins or baskets be removed easily?</li>
    <li>Is the material easy to clean?</li>
    <li>Is it safe for cleaning products?</li>
    <li>Does it suit a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Are daily-use items easy to reach?</li>
    <li>Would removing clutter solve the problem first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-sink kitchen storage works best when it is simple, removable and easy to inspect.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the pipes, leave room for cleaning and maintenance, and choose organisers that make
    the space safer rather than just fuller.
  </p>
